## CRITICAL RULES

### Rule 1: One Class Per File
- NEVER nest classes, interfaces, or records inside other types
- NEVER use local types or anonymous types
- File name MUST match class name (case-sensitive)
- ✅ GOOD: `CreateFenceCommand.cs` containing only `CreateFenceCommand` record
- ❌ WRONG: `Commands.cs` containing multiple command records

### Rule 2: Command/Query Organization
Every Command and Query MUST be organized as:
```
Commands/CreateFence/
├── CreateFenceCommand.cs          (the request record)
├── CreateFenceCommandValidator.cs (input validation)
└── CreateFenceCommandHandler.cs   (business logic)

Queries/GetFenceById/
├── GetFenceByIdQuery.cs           (the request record)
└── GetFenceByIdQueryHandler.cs    (query logic)
```

### Rule 3: Layer Boundaries
```
Domain          (no dependencies except System)
   ↑
Application     (depends on Domain only)
   ↑
Infrastructure  (depends on Domain + Application)
   ↑
Presentation    (depends on Application + Infrastructure)
```

❌ NEVER: Have lower layers depend on upper layers
❌ NEVER: Expose Domain entities in Application layer
❌ NEVER: Expose Application DTOs in Domain layer

### Rule 4: Data Transformation
```
EF Core Entity (FenceEntity)
    ↓ (FenceEntityToDomainMapper)
Domain Aggregate (Fence)
    ↓ (FenceDomainToDtoMapper)
Application DTO (FenceDto)
    ↓ (FenceDtoToViewModelMapper)
Presentation ViewModel (FenceViewModel)
```

Always map at layer boundaries. Never pass entities between layers.

